EIUC / Global Campus of Human Rights, considered the most important academic network in the field of human rights consisting of 100 universities worldwide, and Fondazione Berengo, a Venetian cultural institution which sponsors contemporary art and architecture exhibitions, together  propose to present a supranational pavilion in the context of 2019 Biennale of Art that features artists and art  that  engage with and promote values of human rights.The universal language of art is the most powerful and joyful medium to raise awareness and promote universal human rights.While many works of artists who are activists or who have engaged with human rights through their art, what is missing is a coordinated effort to draw on the full potential of what art can do to promote those values.  The proposed Cosmopolitan Village will fill that void and present a singular platform for:
exhibiting art that provokes a debate on current challenges to human rights;
engaging actively with human rights issues through the lens of the arts and promoting synergies between the two;
fostering a new human rights culture that is coined by dialogue, tolerance and innovation;
connecting artists, members of civil society, NGOs, IOs, politicians and academia through the involvement of the vast network of the Global Campus of Human Rights and the creation of content around the art with seminars, workshops and  conferences;
creating a narrative around the featured art works with academic expertise and educational activities, linking the arts with human rights education and research.  
Where? The headquarters of the two institutions are Palazzo Franchetti by the Grand Canal & a Murano furnace for Fondazione Berengo, and the Monastery of San Nicolò for EIUC/Global Campus of Human Rights.We promise to put your donation to work immediately to establish, organise and present the Cosmopolitan Village in Venice.OTHER WAYS YOU CAN HELPHelp us to promote the event by sharing this campaign using the hashtags:#TogetherForArt #Art4HumanRightsAnd you could always volunteer to help in 2019! *Biennale Arte 2019 - from 11 May to 24 November 2019 (Preview 8-9-10 May)The 58th International Art Exhibition will be titled "May You Live in Interesting Times", a phrase of English invention that has long been mistakenly cited as an ancient Chinese curse that invokes periods of uncertainty, crisis and turmoil; "interesting times", exactly as the ones we live in today. #MayYouLiveInInterestingTimes

Churches Improving Communities (CIC) connects the resources of faith communities - expertise, funding, volunteers, and buildings - with communities in need to improve the lives of hundreds of low-income NJ residents each year via various programs:

NeighborCorps Re-Entry Services, providing support for people returning to their communities from jail;

Church-Based Mental Health Services, providing free and low-cost professional mental health counseling and education at 7 locations in 4 NJ counties; 

CALTR Faith in Action, a volunteer-based service-learning program that rehabilitates homes for low-income families, including those impacted by Hurricane Sandy, and families for whom an affordable rent means the difference between having a home and being homeless; 

New Jersey Congregational Center for Cancer Care (NJ CCCC), a new program that responds to the complexity of cancer in our families and communities through individual, congregational, and systemic engagement, support, and advocacy; and

D.I.R.E. Support Services,  proactive community Deportation & Immigration Response team dedicated to ensuring the human rights and well-being of non-citizen individuals and families in which there are U.S. citizen children living with non-citizen parents.
 100% of donated funds go directly to support the staff and programs that make this work possible. Because CIC partners with faith communities for free building space and a large cadre of volunteers, our program overhead represents just 6% of our total annual budget.In this campaign, we are offering alternative gifts for the holidays. Use the "perks" on the side to chose a particular item or program to donate towards--like counselling costs, sheet rock, and phone services.  It's a wonderful way to give in honor of friends and family! Each donation will come with a personalized card for you to give to your loved ones to let them know what was donated in their honor.Two of our programs are in early stages, so we are directing the funds raised for them in specific ways. Funds donated to DIRE will go towards legal services for low-income individuals, including minors, who require immigration lawyers.  (A typical case starts at $10-12,000. Most families are barely keeping their children fed and housed.)  All donations for New Jersey Congregation Center for Cancer Care will go towards its inaugural year, as we develop programs and hire an executive director.  For each of these, you can choose your level of giving. Your financial support makes a direct impact on the lives of the most vulnerable in New Jersey, people like: 
Ralph, who, despite living in a shelter since his release from jail, was able to receive resume and job interview assistance from NeighborCorps staff and volunteers, and was recently offered three jobs in the same week! Because of the support of this program, he will soon be able to move from the shelter into an apartment and continue to rebuild his life post-incarceration.
Or Bob, a homeowner from Union Beach, who was underinsured and unable to repair his family's home after Hurricane Sandy, and who was able to move back in to a fully functional, safe home thanks to volunteer labor and donated supplies through CALTR.
Or the hundreds of individuals who receive counseling, attend support groups, or participate in mental health education and awareness events each year through Church-Based Mental Health Services, including people who cannot otherwise access services due to prohibitively high insurance deductibles, providers who are too far away for individuals with limited transportation options, or providers with a months-long waiting list for clients to even be seen.
 CIC also utilizes the arts and healing arts to uplift individuals and communities who may benefit from the arts as a way to tell and shape their own stories, as well as to bring the social issues of communities we work with to a larger audience through the arts. Our arts partnerships include:

coLAB Arts to bring awareness of social issues to a broader audience through theatrical and dance performances;
local yoga studios to bring a yoga program into Middlesex County Jail, into a residence for young women aging out of foster care, and to bring trauma-informed yoga training to people involved in helping professions in our community;

the Visual Arts Center of New Jersey, whose teaching artists will be conducting an "art as autobiography" course for inmates;
and Windows of Understanding, a public art partnership with The New Brunswick Community Arts Council, Mason Gross School of the Arts at Rutgers University and the Highland Park Arts Commission, whose theme was "We See Through Hate," a response to hateful political rhetoric.
 CIC relies on the generosity of faith organizations, foundations, and individuals like you to make this work possible.  Please donate today!Classis New Brunswick Community Development Corporation (doing business as Churches Improving Communities) is a 501c3 non-profit organization. All programs are non-discriminatory and open to the public.

Notre campagne de financement est à présent terminée mais vous pouvez toujours verser un don sur notre compte bancaire .Plus d'infos: www.humans-welcome.be/support Chaque matin, lorsque nous prenons notre tasse de café, dans la nuit d’encre précédente, des enfants et des adultes boivent la tasse en Méditerranée, pauvres corps flottant entre deux eaux, dans un cri inaudible tendant la main vers les hommes politiques européens, des millions de réfugiés s’entassent dans des camps de fortune.La Crise du Projet Européen, pauvreté, no future, rejet, repli identitaire/extrême droite/totalitarisme conduisent à la banalité du mal (Hannah Arendt). Le mal ne semble pas affecter les décisions schizophrènes de l’Europe contre les Droits de l’Homme…Des citoyens se mobilisent pour permettre aux réfugiés d’accéder aux droits les plus élémentaires de sécurité, de dignité auxquels tout être humain a droit. Nous demandons plus de justice, nous sommes tous des exilés, aucune civilisation n’a résisté en érigeant des murs.Le projet sur la route des réfugiés s’inscrit dans cette volonté de créer une conscience commune en partant de l’ile de Lesbos (Grèce) pour rejoindre le parlement (caprice des dieux… grecs) à Bruxelles en courant 3.000 km avec des slogans révélateurs de l’irresponsabilité du monde politique européen (Human’s Welcome) et en apportant à nos dirigeants européens un message des réfugiés séjournant en Grèce, ainsi qu’en soutenant les citoyens grecs désespérés (qui est le laboratoire de l’Europe de demain).Quels sont les objectifs ?
Rencontre avec les réfugiés/autorités et peuple grec, artiste Wei Wei/ONG, recevoir leurs messages (en attente des mobilhomes: aux environs du 03/04/2017);
Soutien des associations locales en Grèce œuvrant pour l'accueil et l'intégration des réfugiés;
Départ de Grèce avec les 3 équipes le lendemain de l’arrivée des mobilhomes aux environs du 05 avril 2017 et arrivée au parlement Européen le 16/04/2017;
Parcourir ± 120Km/jour/mobilhome x 3 = 360km durant ± 10 jours (les 3 équipes courent en même temps mais pas ensemble et se retrouvent le soir);
Partager cette conscience dans le voyage en encourageant les habitants (des villes que nous traversons) à courir un peu ensemble (Humans Welcome);
S’arrêter si possible devant les barbelés/frontières en maintenant une minute de silence/brassard noir du deuil;
A l’arrivée en Belgique (si possible beaucoup de coureurs rejoignent la caravane pour arriver à Bruxelles), interpeller les hommes politiques européens avec le message transmis par les réfugiés et le peuple grec (demander le soutien de parlementaires européens);
Déposer sur le parvis, un zodiac avec les photos de Humans Welcome et des gilets de sauvetage;
Par la suite, projections du voyage/démarches dans les écoles !
À quoi serviront les dons récoltés via cette campagne de financement ?Les dons serviront dans un premier temps, à financer les coûts de location, ainsi que les différents frais connexes, des mobilhomes afin d'accompagner les coureurs, dans la remontée, vers le Parlement Européen à Bruxelles en Belgique.Au delà des 15.000€, les dons iront à des associations œuvrant pour l'accueil et l'intégration des réfugiés.Les frais personnels des coureurs ne sont pas pris en compte dans le montant de notre campagne de financement dans la mesure où ceux-ci sont pris en charge par les coureurs eux-mêmes.Grâce à vous, nous serons leurs pas, leurs voix... Merci pour eux !
